  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      Colon cancer is the second most common cause of death among cancer-related deaths in Germany.
      Precancerous lesions such as adenomas can be detected efficiently by colonoscopy. To provide
      high quality in colonoscopy several quality parameters have been postulated in the past. The
      adenoma detection rate (ADR) is one of those parameters. Empirical data suggest that a
      detection rate of 20% should be demanded. Detection rates are influenced by a multitude of
      circumstances such as bowel cleanness. The facts that detection rates vary between
      colonoscopists suggests that leaning effects may also play a role. It is not known how ADR
      and other quality parameters evolve while trainees improve their skills in colonoscopy. The
      investigators postulate that a learning curve exists. The investigators therefore plan to
      evaluate chronologically the findings of trainee colonoscopists. A particular performance in
      detecting adenomas shall be calculated in relation to the amount of examinations performed.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
